Unfortunately, this is not the tone of many meetings, and the promise of "more generous and kind" policies, if they ever existed, has long since been forgotten.
It is increasingly evident that divergent opinions are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and each opinion is judged on whether it is acceptable to the party leadership.
This started shortly after Jeremy became leader, as colleagues with whom I once thought I shared a similar political vision expected me to make a U-turn and take positions I would never have taken, whether it was on national security or the EU single market.
Whenever I speak in public, whatever I say, social media is flooded with aggressive messages calling for my candidacy not to be renewed, denouncing centre-left policies and saying I shouldn't be in the Labour Party.
And this is not just happening to me.
In fact, I know I'm luckier than some of my colleagues, because the messages I get are usually political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of colleagues who every day have to face a torrent of sexist and racist attacks, and they do not get mad.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is to see how the level of abuse has become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn declared last week that the Labour Party should foster a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that diverse party, and with every motion of no confidence or every change in the selection rules, the party is getting smaller.
I've had a lot of advice over the last couple of years, and it's been, "Keep your head down, don't be so expressive, and everything will be fine".
But I didn't go into politics for that.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago, as a student, spurred on by the negligent Thatcher government, which literally left my entire class in the dust, I have tried to advocate for better public services for those who need them most, whether as a local councillor or as a government minister.
I've never hidden my politics, not even in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could in any way doubt my political positions and points of disagreement with the current leadership.
To those who pushed the motion on Friday, I would say that at a time when the country is moving towards a Brexit that will hurt homes, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But, in fact, the message I want to convey is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise you that no threat of not renewing my candidacy or any political interest will prevent me from acting, in my opinion, in the best interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is the Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
