The sea is ours: Landlocked Bolivia hopes court reopens Pacific route
Sailors patrol their covered naval shipyard in La Paz.
Public buildings are flown with a navy blue flag.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are empowered with the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
To get it back is a duty.
Across Bolivia's landlocked territory, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict remains very vivid, as does the longing to sail across the Pacific Ocean again.
These hopes are perhaps the deepest in decades, as Bolivia awaits the resolution that the International Court of Justice will issue on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and, needless to say, it is waiting with a positive attitude for the result", pointed out Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will be watching the TIJ decision on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague Court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile is obliged to negotiate the granting of a sovereign outlet to the sea for Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who faces a controversial re-election battle next year, also has high hopes for Monday's resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean", he promised last August.
However, some analysts think it is unlikely that the Court will rule in favor of Bolivia and that if it does, things will not change much.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to award Chilean territory and has stated that it will not determine the outcome of the possible talks.
The TIJ's resolution, which comes just six months after the final allegations were filed, indicates that the case "was not complicated", Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law, said.
And far from being favored, Bolivia's cause may have experienced a setback in the last four years.
"The current Bolivian administration has hijacked the issue of access to the sea", Zárate noted.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any gesture of goodwill on the part of Chile, he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk for a while, but it will be very difficult to have conversations after this episode.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was exceptionally rapid.
Next Monday Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who remains one of Latin America's most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean", he added.
Resolution is an opportunity to realize that we have to overcome the past.
