John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career of their choice and for their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages remain a very popular and desired choice subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head".
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's examinations, we can see that languages lead the ranking tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained the top grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained an upper A qualification in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as an elective subject, are held in the same regard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in curricula from independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave for finding it difficult to fill vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more potential job opportunities require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language education is important for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find a meaningful job.
In Scotland there is diversity between schools in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK in the future, towards 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, he or she can always choose from a range of languages in independent schools, which have specialist teaching staff.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In today's global business environment, it is undeniable that languages remain of vital importance for the future of the country, and this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It must be done well.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
