North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm any way if signs of trust are not appreciated
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying his mistrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons in any way.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any response in line with the US", he said.
Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not initiate disarmament unilaterally in any way.
While Ri took up North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization approach whereby North Korea would be rewarded as it took steps step by step, his statements seemed significant in that he did not reject full unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang had already done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump made at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has attempted to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
The US insists that denuclearization must occur first and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, in addition to opposing the declaration of end of the war, Ri noted.
The perception that sanctions will bring us to our knees is a chimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuous sanctions are intensifying our mistrust.
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader outlined at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party involved in the denuclearization issue were South Korea instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this stalemate".
However, Ri's tone was very different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the US mainland with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President Trump dubbed Kim "Rocket Man" in a suicide mission.
At the United Nations last year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still much to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearises.
Last Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this and that "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo declared to the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without exception until we confirm complete and final denuclearization".
The Security Council has pushed sanctions on North Korea unanimously since 2006 in a bid to cut off funding for Pyongyang's ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later communicated that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go very well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but within hours North Korea accused him of making "gangster-like demands".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile center and a nuclear complex if the United States took "consonant action".
He said Kim had communicated to him that the "consistent measures" he was seeking were the security measures Trump had promised in Singapore, in addition to actions toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a class on resting habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of all-night study stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that students at the world's top universities are often misled about the basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
And at the end of the talk, this girl came up to me and said, "Why are they telling me this now, my senior year?"
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first implemented this year, teaches students the basics of how good sleep habits improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, stated that the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one section is a picture of a dorm room, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, banners and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance affects sleep deprivation, and the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
We know that student behavior won't change overnight.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes", Professor Czeisler noted.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students make sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Ensuring that they get enough quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode and makes students hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes in his last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask graduate students to undertake a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
