The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
New research on a farm in the Highlands of Scotland aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed.
It is hoped that the discoveries may provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern eared and water bats at Inverewe Botanic Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK National Health Service will also carry out mobile surveys with portable detectors.
Experts' analysis of the sound recordings will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and habitat map will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser at the National Trust for Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Building construction and restoration tasks threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do paper mosquitoes and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to locate insects and obstacles that get in the way of their flight.
The National Trust for Scotland, responsible for caring for over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the proper training, who conduct surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues on a regular basis.
In fact, the organisation has created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
"Here in Threave, we have a large area for bats", he says.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.
He notes the importance of checking for bats before doing maintenance work on properties, as the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest could kill more than 400 females and young, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, attack them, harass them, and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer with the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to step forward to help.
He stated the following: "We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our own species, we do not have enough data on their population".
